The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                 
	Bridgetown: Andrew Strauss has given his strongest backing to Andy Flower as the England and Wales Cricket Board (ECB) prepares for the interview stage of the task of replacing Peter Moores in the revamped position of England performance director. Strauss is being kept in the loop without having a say in the appointment, but on Thursday, he made his preference all but explicit.    
	Flower is leaving a solid impression for his work as the acting head coach in the Caribbean and is understood to be the favoured candidate of the ECB.         
	Melbourne: Former Australian star Mark Waugh feels that Rahul Dravid is not a natural slip catcher but has a great concentration which has taken him on the brink of becoming the player with most catches in Test cricket. Dravid is good but hes got a funny style. Hes not a natural catcher but hes got great concentration and hes in the right place at the right time, Waugh said.        
	Calcutta: The India-born Vikram Solanki is the new president of the Professional Cricketers Association in England. He had to ward off the challenge of five other claimants for the post in a keenly-fought contest.        
	Karachi: Pakistans former Test player and current fielding coach of the national team, Ijaz Ahmed, has been shifted to a hospital in Lahore after he suffered a severe asthma attack at the Gulberg Liberty police station. Ijaz was arrested Friday in a fraud case and put behind bars but suffered an asthma attack late Friday night.        
	Shenzhen: Indias Rashid Khan returned a card of two-under 70 to retain the Faldo Series Asia title at the Mission Hills Golf Club on Friday. Rashid, who has won four titles on the LG Amateur Tour, finished with a three-day total of five-under 211, to clinch the title in under-18 event.          
	Hua Hin (Thailand): Anirban Lahiri leapfrogged to tied 12th with a sedate second round of two-under 70 even though only four Indians made the cut in the $ 500,000 Black Mountain Masters golf tournament here Friday. Gaganjeet Bhullar and Rahil Gangjee (142) hung out for weekend action sharing the 38th spot after both carded their second straight round of 71 today. Swede Johan Edfors was in the lead.        
	New Delhi: Hungarian coach Imre Zsuga is all set to be made the Indian weightlifting head coach with the aim to secure maximum medals for the country in the 2010 Commonwealth Games. Zsugas name has been cleared by the Sports Authority of India (SAI).    
